<p>Tanzania&#x27;s general election on and around Oct. 29 saw large protests in major cities after opposition figures were arrested or barred from running, prompting authorities to impose a nationwide 6pm–6am curfew and disrupt internet access to restore order . Demonstrations took place in Dar es Salaam and Arusha and at times turned violent, with police using tear gas and firing shots to disperse crowds while some vehicles and public infrastructure were damaged . Incumbent President Samia Suluhu Hassan is widely expected to win a second term amid criticism that the main opposition was effectively excluded from the vote, a development observers and activists have linked to a tightening political environment .</p><img src='https://kagiproxy.com/img/03VDPT8YMuQTYuTZ_7C13oPq-RytqTZMgvJ623InbND5q6mff3a-L7hSNA-qtSPwkbAyqU99Xt9p7Ie0J29IXyrfmueL2UZfgHsEx80R3-S2mzfnsMVyoakeHXwEkidOhDrUpEWE066bFapcZopxwlenmnFK055zAIdCD07lLWfU0onkj13rTPYq6RY4oyrW5ZVZO5rL8s4AyItGlF4kI7409fD_bThzHpKO_cW0n3OV1pbPuNIq4w' alt='Voters casting ballots in Stone Town, Zanzibar, during Tanzania’s general election.' /><br /><h3>Highlights:</h3><ul><li>Historic demonstrations: Citizens demonstrated in significant numbers for the first time in 65 years, according to local reporting about the unrest that accompanied voting .</li><li>Schools and work: After unrest during voting, the government advised students and some government workers to stay home to reduce risks and maintain public order .</li><li>Damage reported: Protesters set fire to vehicles and damaged public infrastructure in parts of Dar es Salaam, prompting renewed police dispersal measures the day after the vote .</li><li>Political context: Analysts and reporting link the unrest to a political environment in which the long-ruling party aims to retain control amid restrictions on opposition activity .</li></ul><h3>Perspectives:</h3><ul><li>Tanzanian rights activists: Civil society voices described the vote as lacking genuine competition and criticized legal and security steps taken against opposition figures . (<a href='https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/2025/10/29/tanzania-election-president-samia-suluhu-hassan-opposition/'>Washington Post</a>)</li><li>Ruling party analysts / reporting: Coverage notes that the Party of Revolution and its allies moved to preserve political dominance in an election where main challengers were excluded by legal and administrative measures . (<a href='https://www.nytimes.com/2025/10/29/world/africa/tanzania-presidential-election.html'>The New York Times; Foreign Policy</a>)</li></ul><h3>Sources:</h3><ul><li><a href='https://allafrica.com/stories/202510300016.html'>Tanzania: Curfew, Internet Blackout as Tanzania Election Day Descends into Chaos</a> - allafrica.com</li><li><a href='https://www.nytimes.com/2025/10/29/world/africa/tanzania-presidential-election.html'>Protests in Tanzania as Voters Head to the Polls</a> - nytimes.com</li><li><a href='https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/2025/10/29/tanzania-election-president-samia-suluhu-hassan-opposition/'>Election protests erupt in Tanzania with opposition leaders jailed, disqualified</a> - washingtonpost.com</li><li><a href='https://www.france24.com/en/tv-shows/eye-on-africa/20251029-protests-erupt-as-tanzania-holds-contentious-election'>Protests erupt as Tanzania holds contentious election</a> - france24.com</li><li><a href='https://foreignpolicy.com/2025/10/29/tanzania-unfree-election-cameroon-ivory-coast-protest-sudan-conflict/'>Tanzania’s Unfree Election</a> - foreignpolicy.com</li><li><a href='https://www.dw.com/en/tanzania-tells-students-to-stay-home-after-tense-election/a-74550928'>Tanzania tells students to stay home after tense election</a> - dw.com</li><li><a href='https://www.straitstimes.com/world/New-protests-in-Tanzanias-main-city-after-chaotic-election'>New protests in Tanzania&#x27;s main city after chaotic election</a> - straitstimes.com</li></ul>